  "prompt": "How does a half moon happen?",
  "response": "A half moon happens because of the relative positions of the Sun, Earth, and Moon. Here's a breakdown:\n\n*   **The Moon doesn't produce its own light:** We see the Moon because it reflects sunlight.\n\n*   **The Moon orbits the Earth:** As the Moon orbits us, different amounts of its sunlit surface become visible from Earth.\n\n*   **Halfway through the cycle:** When the Moon is roughly at a right angle (90 degrees) to the Earth relative to the Sun, we see half of the Moon illuminated and half in shadow. This occurs twice during each lunar cycle:\n\n    *   **First Quarter Moon:** This happens about a week after the New Moon. The right half of the Moon appears lit.\n\n    *   **Third Quarter Moon:** This happens about a week after the Full Moon. The left half of the Moon appears lit.\n\n**In summary:** A half moon occurs when we see exactly half of the Moon's sunlit surface from Earth, a position that is reached twice in the lunar cycle at the first and third quarter phases.\n",
